summary:
The patient’s pain localized to the sole of the foot during leg elevation—triggered by exertion and relieved by rest—is characteristic of ischemic claudication from peripheral arterial disease. Despite an unusual trigger (elevation rather than ambulation), the combination of classic risk factors, absent pedal pulses, and exclusion of other causes such as nerve compression or deep vein thrombosis supports femoropopliteal artery stenosis as the correct diagnosis.  

\boxed{A} 

Note: This summary focuses only on clinically significant elements directly tied to diagnosing PAD versus alternative explanations; no extraneous details about smoking duration or BP values were included beyond their relevance to establishing overall cardiovascular risk profile.

